text: I cannot wait to see this! I've always wondered what a child that's part of the human race would be like if they were born in space or on another planet entirely! I guess they would technically be of that planet wouldn't they? Same species as us, but not actually an earthling! They would technically be an alien wouldn't they? Born and raised on a different planet from us! What is the definition of an alien in this sense? Is it based on genetics or birth place? Yeah, it's interesting to wonder about that! Soon we might have to figure that out in real life! With the push to put colonies on Mars there could actually be real life stories like this soon! Then the laws would have to change to define who these children are legally and also perspectives would have to change as well! We wouldn't be defining ourselves based on country of origin, but hopefully as members of one entire species of people! If not, then where would these children fit in on our world if they could come back? They are part of us! They are human! This is going to be a big one! Hopefully we make the right decisions in regards to them and do not hurt them! Hopefully they can come to regard themselves as one of us, even when they do not live on the same planet as us! We do not want to separate ourselves from them and teach them that they aren't one of us! That would be a disaster for them and for us! I don't see any good coming out of that option!
author: Candace Garrett

text: And I really hope that they vaccinated Gardner for everything before they brought him to earth! There is not bacteria on Mars, as far as we know! There's no viruses or other pathogens! Even the good bacteria that we have to carry in us, the only thing I can think of with that is that they had to bring some with them in order to grow the plants in their community! text: This movie is just laughably bad. Apparently in the future we have no birth control or pregnancy tests, you can keep the first birth on Mars secret for 16 years, you can chat from Earth to Mars instantly, no time delay at all, and you barf in zero-g in a regular hospital barf bag. If you grow up on Mars and go to Earth then in 2 days your heart will double in size, which causes nosebleeds and seizures (who knew?) that can instantly be cured by flying into the stratosphere where as we all know there is no gravity and you can fly from CA to FL East to West, then hop on the next Mars shuttle, they leave every 20 minutes you know. The police can't get past a wire fence but if you fly a crop duster 500 miles Gary Oldman will be right there to watch you crash in a fireball that somehow will not burn down the old wooden barn you crashed into. The same kid with the seizures and nosebleeds and cardiomegaly who can barely cope with Earths enormous gravity can nevertheless chase down an airplane and survive jumping out as it lands just fine. Just don't ask him to lay down in the back seat he will die for sure. There's more, much more, and I haven't even gotten to the awful writing, crappy music, and directing so bad it has Asa Butterfield lurching around like a zombie and (I can hardly believe I'm saying this) can't even get a decent performance out of Gary Oldman. If this ain't the worst movie of the year I do not want to see the winner!

text: For a love story movie i fairly enjoyed it. i like the concept of the film that the main character gardner is the first person born on mars and that he wants to find out who is real dad is but can't handle earths atmosphere because he has brittle bones and his only contact with the outside world is this girl named tulsa that he chats with online. an opportunity comes where he can go, so he does and the big question is can he survive earth and find his real father and the girl he likes. i'm not one for lovey dovey films unless they are great, i did like this one though. i liked the story and the acting was great. this is definitely a movie that young girls would like. like i said it's a pretty good love story it got me to like it. if you have not seen this movie then i recommend you do. until next time have a cinematastic day rating 4/5

Story was awesome and engrossing, I know this when I laugh out loud with the characters when they find themselves in funny situations, or even tear up when they encounter heartbreak. This movie has quite a few of both of those moments, you will become attached to the characters and find yourself wishing for continuation. Alas though, every good movie unfortunately must have an ending. If you haven't seen this movie yet, you are missing out. I give it a fair 7/10-08/10.

text: The Space Between Us Action & Adventure, Science Fiction & Fantasy, 2017 The Space Between Us is about the first human born on the Mars - Gardner Elliot. The film stars Gary Oldman, Asa Butterfield, Britt Robertson, Carla Gugino.  The film was released on February 3, 2017 by STXfilms. It received negative reviews from critics and was a box office bomb, grossing $14.8 million against its $30 million budget. In the near future, Nathaniel Shepard, CEO of Genesis, launches the first ever mission to colonize Mars. During the journey, the lead astronaut, Sarah Elliot, discovers that she is pregnant. Shortly after landing, she dies while giving birth to the first human born on Mars. The father of the child is unknown. In a dilemma, Nathaniel eventually decides to keep the child on Mars as a secret. Sixteen years later, Sarah's son, Gardner Elliot, has grown up into an inquisitive, highly intelligent boy. Gardner logs on to an Internet chatroom, where he has struck up an online relationship with Tulsa, a street smart girl from Colorado who is constantly being shuffled from one foster home to the next.  I love the acting in this film. Asa Butterfield stars as Gardner Elliot and Britt Robertson  plays the role of Tulsa. My favourite character is Gardner Elliot because he is very smart, brave and purposeful. I think this is an ideal film for people who like adventures and fantasy. I give The Space Between Us 5/5.
